  "prompt": "What is a doppelganger? What are some examples?",
  "response": "## What is a Doppelganger?\n\nA doppelganger is a **non-biologically related look-alike or double of a living person.** The word comes from German, meaning \"double-goer\" or \"double walker.\"\n\nTraditionally, doppelgangers are often considered **omens of bad luck or even death**. In folklore, seeing your own doppelganger is believed to be a harbinger of your demise. In some cultures, they are seen as malevolent spirits or shadowy counterparts meant to replace or impersonate the original person.\n\nHowever, the concept has expanded beyond these ominous roots. Today, the term doppelganger can also simply refer to someone who bears a striking resemblance to another person, regardless of supernatural connotations.\n\n**Key Characteristics of a Doppelganger:**\n\n*   **Physical Resemblance:** The most defining feature is a strong physical similarity to the original person.\n*   **Not Genetically Related:** Doppelgangers are not twins or relatives; they are unrelated individuals.\n*   **Psychological Effect:**  The phenomenon can be unsettling or fascinating for the person being mirrored and for others.\n*   **Supernatural Connotations (Traditionally):** Historically linked to omens, bad luck, and impending death.\n\n## Examples of Doppelgangers:\n\nHere are some examples of doppelgangers, spanning from folklore and literature to real-life instances and modern interpretations:\n\n**1.  Folklore and Mythology:**\n\n*   **The Evil Twin/Shadow Self:** Many cultures have stories of evil or shadowy versions of individuals who act as antagonists or temptations.\n*   **The Changeling:**  In European folklore, a changeling is a creature (often a fairy) left in place of a human child who has been stolen. It's a type of doppelganger where the imposter is a different species.\n\n**2.  Literature:**\n\n*   **\"The Strange Case of Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde\" by Robert Louis Stevenson:** This classic explores the duality of human nature with Dr. Jekyll creating an alter ego, Mr. Hyde, who embodies his darker side. While not a perfect doppelganger in the traditional sense, it explores the concept of a second self existing within the same person.\n*   **\"The Double\" by Fyodor Dostoevsky:** A man named Golyadkin encounters a person who is his exact double. This double slowly takes over his life, causing Golyadkin to lose his sanity.\n*   **\"The Picture of Dorian Gray\" by Oscar Wilde:** The portrait of Dorian Gray ages and reflects his moral decay, acting as a doppelganger of his inner self.\n*   **\"Harry Potter\" Series by J.K. Rowling:** Barty Crouch Jr. uses Polyjuice Potion to impersonate Mad-Eye Moody, effectively becoming a doppelganger for an extended period.\n\n**3.  Real-Life Examples & Modern Interpretations:**\n\n*   **Celebrity Look-alikes:**  The internet is full of examples of ordinary people who bear striking resemblances to celebrities. These can go viral and generate interest.\n*   **\"Stranger Things\" Characters:** The character of Eleven and her \"sister\" Kali (008) are essentially evil doppelgangers because of the experiments they underwent at Hawkins National Laboratory.\n*   **Modern Psychological Interpretations:**  Some psychologists see doppelganger experiences as related to dissociative disorders, feelings of alienation, or distortions in self-perception.  Others see them as coincidence and the human tendency to recognize patterns, even when they don't fully exist.\n*   **Facial Recognition Software Issues:**  There have been cases where facial recognition software has misidentified individuals as someone else, creating a digital doppelganger effect. This highlights the limitations and potential biases of AI systems.\n\n**4.  Historical Examples (Often with Anecdotal Evidence):**\n\n*   **Abraham Lincoln:** Supposedly, Lincoln saw a double reflection of himself in a mirror shortly before his assassination, which was interpreted as a sign of his impending death. (Note: this is anecdotal and likely embellished).\n*   **Queen Elizabeth I:**  Stories circulated about Queen Elizabeth I having encountered her own doppelganger, taken as an ill omen.\n\n**In Summary:**\n\nThe concept of a doppelganger has evolved over time. While it originally carried sinister connotations, today it can simply refer to someone who looks remarkably like another person, sparking curiosity and raising questions about identity, individuality, and the strangeness of human existence.  The modern interpretation is often more about coincidence and visual similarity than about supernatural threats.\n",
